<section id="clsEventNotification"><title>EventNotification Mixin Class</title>
<indexterm><primary>EventNotification class</primary></indexterm>
<para>
  The event notification class is a <emphasis role="italic">Mixin</emphasis> class that contains methods that connect a
  <link linkend="ovvEvents">window event</link> with a method in the Rexx dialog object. Except as noted below, the Rexx
  programmer adds the method to her dialog subclass. Once the event is connected, each time the event occurs in the
  dialog, the connected method is invoked.  The programmer codes the method to take the appropiate action for the event.
</para>
<para>
  Whenever a dialog object is instantiated, three event connections are automatically made. They connect the <emphasis
  role="italic">ok</emphasis>, <emphasis role="italic">cancel</emphasis>, and <emphasis role="italic">help</emphasis>
  events to the <link linkend="mthOk">ok</link>(), <link linkend="mthCancel">cancel</link>(), and <link
  linkend="mthHelp">help</link>() methods of the dialog object. The <emphasis role="italic">ok</emphasis>() and
  <emphasis role="italic">cancel</emphasis>() methods are already coded to take the appropriate default action. The
  default action for the <emphasis role="italic">help</emphasis>() method is to do nothing.  All three methods are
  intended to be over-ridden by the programmer if the default action is not sufficient.
</para>
<para>
  For all other events the Rexx programmer needs to specifically connect the event to his dialog, through one of the
  event notification methods, to be able to respond to the event.  Indeed, except for trivial dialogs, most of the
  programming is deciding which events to be notified of and taking action upon receiving the notification.
</para>
<para>
  The <link linkend="clsEventNotification">EventNotification</link> class implements all the methods that create a
  connection between a <link linkend="ovvEvents">window event</link> and a method of the Rexx dialog object. In the
  Windows user interface, as the user interacts with the system, events are generated that specify what the action of
  the user was. Mouse clicks, keyboard presses, moving or sizing windows, all generate events. In the ooDialogframework,
  when a specific event is connected to a method in a dialog object, that method will be invoked each time the event
  occurs.
</para>
<para>
  Some simple examples of how this works:
<itemizedlist>
<listitem>
<para>
  For push buttons you connect a method to the button. The connected method is called each time the button is pressed
  (clicked.)
</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>
  List boxes, multiple-select list boxes, and combo boxes can be connected to a method that is called each time a line
  in the box is selected.
</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>
  For a scroll bar you can specify different methods that are called depending on the user action. The user can click on
  the arrow buttons, drag the thumb, or use the page down / page up keys.
</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>
  In a <computeroutput>UserDialog</computeroutput> some of the methods that create dialog controls have an option that
  automatically connects an event to a dialog method. However, for most events, say the resize or move events, the
  connection needs to be made explicitly.  In general, events should be connected before the dialog is shown on the
  screen. So, the connect event methods can be used in the <link linkend="mthInitDialog">initDialog</link>() method.  In
  a UserDialog, the <link linkend="mthDefineDialog">defineDialog</link>() method is a good place for the connect event methods.
  If the programmer is overriding the <link linkend="h000025">init</link>() method, the connect event methods can be
  placed there.  But, in this case, do not invoke the connect event methods until after the superclass has been
  initialized.
</para>

<note><title>Note</title><para>
  The method name that is to be invoked when the specified event occurs must be less than 256 characters.
</para></note>
<para>
  All event connection methods are in the <emphasis role="italic">EventNotification</emphasis> class. The event
  notification class is inherited by the base dialog class, the <link linkend="clsPlainBaseDialog">PlainBaseDialog
  </link>class. Therefore the methods of the class are a part of every dialog.
</para>

